Have you heard the story about water?

The drip from a continuous stream of water kept hitting the same stone over and over and over. After quite some time, the stone started to erode. It started shrinking. How? Who would’ve thought that a substance as light and flexible as water could wear down an object as stiff and solid as stone?

Well, it did. And, that parable is inspiration when it comes to talking about the power of belief.

I remember watching a quick video on social media with the ever talented actor, Anthony Hopkins, speaking with great fervor about “playing the game of belief.” To me, it was a great way to drive home the message of sticking with something until you see the results you want to get. And, the extra bonus is the person you become while going after those results.

I’ve held on to several beliefs over the years, and some things didn’t manifest until years later. Heck, I’m still dripping that proverbial water and waiting on some of those dreams to happen. None-the-less, by “playing the game of belief” I’ve given myself more chances to win; created more opportunities to grow; and experienced some pretty dope surprises along the way just because I put myself in position by believing.

Believing in my vision. 
Believing in a plan.
Believing it’s possible.
Believing in myself.
.
#CoachRho

#BlackoutTuesday for #TyreNichols … WARNING: Graphic photo shared on the 3rd slide.

It has taken me some time to process this situation. So incredibly sad to see what happened to him. As most of you know, I have had major issues with police and the abuse of power. No matter the motivation behind their brutality, the fact that they feel they can commit horrendous crimes behind that badge is beyond disheartening.

There is a culture in policing that has to be addressed.

Beyond social media, I have been having several conversations about what can be done to address that culture. I have been educating myself and exploring how I can be apart of solutions.

It’s not an energy I want to keep revisiting, but social justice is not necessarily about what I want to do, it is about what needs to be done.

God bless all the families that are affected by this. And hopefully by exposing the public to these videos, it puts other ‘bad cops’ on notice and changes their decision to act so heinously. #SocialJustice #AbuseOfPower

Nurturing Your Dreams... #SundaySoulFood 

Are you feeling stuck? Do you feel like giving up? You're not alone. Achieving your goals can be challenging, but it's important to remember that success takes time and effort. Just like nurturing a child or starting a business, it requires patience, dedication and persistence.

I remember when I started PPU. It was a bit overwhelming at first, but I broke down my big vision into smaller more manageable tasks. I celebrated my small victories along the way and it helped me to stay motivated and focused. I also found inspiration in other successful entrepreneurs who had gone through similar challenges.

Tips:

Breaking down big goals into to more manageable tasks helps to make the goal less intimidating.

Celebrating small victories helps you to recognize your progress and can keep you motivated for the long haul.

Finding inspiration in other people who have gone through similar challenges and feelings of fear and anxiousness can help you learn from their experiences and push you to what YOU are capable of.

A quote to keep you going:

"Success is not final, failure is not fatal; it is the courage to continue that counts." - Winston Churchill

As I like to say so often... 'Fail Forward'

Coach Rho

Cali... you ready? Uncle Charlie and En Vogue tonight at the Hollywood Bowl.

I remember when I first moved to Cali and would see droves of cars coming in and out of the Hollywood Bowl concert venue. I'd never gone inside and would think about one day being able to perform there. Some years back, we got the opportunity in connection with another show, and that dream was realized. 

Tonight, we get to do a concert with Charlie Wilson. He was a part of my mom's favorite group, The Gap Band. I would listen to their vinyl records when I was younger. It's a treat to have these two nostalgic highlights, for me, merge into one place. I'm grateful 🙏🏾 and hope to see you there. ✨🤛🏽🧡
.

Some of us feel we have to settle for difficult relationships with others, and so we give up on believing things can be better. 

A couple days ago, I put up a message looking for 3 men who feel socially awkward and want to keep meaningful connections. It was to address those already having difficulty and needing help with interaction and communication.

You know, like I know, that men AND women can suffer with this no matter the social situation. However, keeping in line with men who need help in this area, I want to share Chiest's story. 

His efforts prove that companionship, care, and protection of loved ones is still possible.

Here are his words:

"I was told by a friend, “When you travel, you find pieces of yourself around the world.” That’s what comes to mind when I think of Coach Rho, but I’ll take it even a step further. I didn’t just find myself, I created myself. My mind expanded, and I was exposed to deeper meaning and connections. I was witnessing a person who was OK with showing her imperfections, her insecurities, but didn’t mask herself in them. Balance and integrity, unconditional love and patience. I understand life better because she made me feel comfortable getting uncomfortable. Words can’t express how I feel when I talk about the woman who changed the future generations of my family; from what she’s taught, exposed me to, and showed in her actions. My grandmother has taken leaps and bounds in her health in her 70’s. My mother reached down and grew the child inside of her up that needed her, and family members have forgiven each other and confronted past secrets that haunt us at family gathering for generations.

My son’s mom and I stop battling in court and my father and I have a great relationship after he was never there. You taught me what being present is; what love is; what life can be if you allow it. You taught me my life was my choice, and you never gave up on me when I fell…. All because you allowed the Universe to use you. I found and created pieces of me around the world … through PPU. Thank you, love you coach."

Embrace the Discomfort, Compete with Yourself, and Prioritize Self-Care for Personal and Professional Growth

In the journey of personal and professional development, there are three powerful principles that can pave the way for success: getting comfortable with being uncomfortable, understanding that your only competitor is the person you were yesterday, and incorporating de-stressing activities into your self-care routine.

1. Embrace the Discomfort:

One of the most profound ways to grow is by stepping outside your comfort zone. It's in the discomfort that true learning and progress occur. Whether it's taking on a challenging project at work, learning a new skill, or facing your fears, embracing discomfort is a crucial aspect of personal development. Instead of shying away from challenges, lean into them. Every moment of discomfort is an opportunity to learn, adapt, and ultimately become a stronger and more resilient individual.

2. Compete with Yourself:

Comparing yourself to others can be a slippery slope, often leading to feelings of inadequacy or unwarranted superiority. The only competition that truly matters is the one you have with yourself. Focus on becoming a better version of who you were yesterday. Set personal goals, celebrate small victories, and continuously strive for improvement. This mindset shift not only fosters a healthier self-image but also ensures that your energy is directed towards constructive self-growth rather than external validation.

3. De-Stress for Success:

In the hustle and bustle of personal and professional development, it's easy to overlook the importance of self-care. De-stressing activities play a vital role in maintaining a harmonious and healthy lifestyle. Whether it's meditation, exercise, reading, or spending time with loved ones, incorporating these activities into your routine is essential. Stress is a natural part of growth, but managing it effectively ensures that you can operate at your best. Taking care of your mental and physical well-being is not a sign of weakness but rather a strategic move toward sustained success.
